A Zendesk MCP server acts as a bridge between AI assistants and the Zendesk API, enabling natural language management of tickets, users, organizations, and Help Center content [1][2][3][4][5]. Multiple independent implementations exist, ranging from lightweight ticket-focused servers to comprehensive suites offering 60+ tools [6][7].

These servers typically support two transport modes: Stdio for local CLI-based clients (e.g., Claude Desktop, Cursor) and HTTP/SSE for remote or web-based integration [1][2][7]. Most support authentication via Zendesk API tokens or OAuth 2.1 with PKCE [1][3][7].

To use one, configure the server in your MCP client's settings:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "zendesk": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@markusvankempen/zendesk-mcp-server"],
      "env": {
        "ZENDESK_SUBDOMAIN": "your-subdomain",
        "ZENDESK_EMAIL": "agent@example.com",
        "ZENDESK_API_TOKEN": "your-token"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Implementation details like tool naming conventions, available functionality, and flag configurations (such as `--mode` for filtering tools) vary by specific repository [1][3][7][5].
